    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-24T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-24T06:00:00-05:00" n="472"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d472">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.01/160: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-24T11:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 24, 1919, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4796. For the Secretary of State from <persName corresp="#p_PFL"
                    >Polk</persName>.</p>
                <p>Your telegram[s] in regard to recognition of <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1"
                        >Kolchak</persName> received. I spoke to the British as I reported but
                        <persName corresp="#p_CSE1">Eyre Crowe</persName>
                    <note n="89" xml:id="d472fn89">Sir <persName corresp="#p_CSE1">Eyre
                            Crowe</persName>, member of the British delegation at the Peace
                        Conference.</note> apparently has no instructions. <persName
                        corresp="#p_PS1">Pichon</persName> seems to be entirely in favor of it being
                    done and thinks now is the time to do so. I suggest that if you are in favor of
                    recognition of <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName>, the United
                    States should take the lead as Great Britain and France are merely waiting for
                    an opportunity to follow. In view of all the help given <persName
                        corresp="#p_DGAI">Denikin</persName> by England, I think it would help our
                    prestige to take the lead in recognition. As Petrograd may be taken soon it
                    would be better to grant recognition now, if you intend ultimately to grant
                    recognition, rather than to wait.</p>
                <p>I had a conversation with <persName>Lvoff</persName>
                    <note n="90" xml:id="d472fn90">Prince <persName>George E. Lvov</persName>,
                        former premier of the Russian Provisional Government.</note> and he begged
                    earnestly for recognition of <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName> at
                    the earliest possible moment. He said that, in his opinion, it would help in
                    keeping in check the reactionary army people, also he stated that the Russians
                    were having a great deal of trouble with Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BND1"
                        >Baker</persName> in regard to Russian supplies. He said that the British
                    had done a great deal, not only for <persName corresp="#p_DGAI"
                        >Denikin</persName> but for <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName>
                    but apparently we had not been able to deliver supplies we expected to deliver
                    owing to the opposition of the Secretary of War.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Mission</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
